## Preface, 2002

### The Triumph of Economic Freedom (1962-2002)
- **Dramatic shift in climate of opinion** between 1962 publication and 1980s: from hostility to respectability
- **Government spending explosion**: 1956: 26% of national income (12% non-defense); 1982: 39% (31% non-defense); 2000: 36% (30% non-defense)
- **Electoral consequences**: Thatcher in Britain, Reagan in US rode wave of changing opinion, though unable to reverse spending growth

### The Berlin Wall and Soviet Collapse
- **1989-1992**: Natural experiment between economic systems reached dramatic conclusion
- Smaller-scale precedents confirmed: Hong Kong/Taiwan vs mainland China; West Germany vs East Germany; South Korea vs North Korea
- **Friedrich A. Hayek's** *The Road to Serfdom* (1944) vindicated—central planning now accepted as path to economic failure
- Pattern repeated across Western countries: postwar socialism → creeping/stagnant socialism → pressure toward markets

### The Global Turn to Markets
- **China under Deng Xiaoping** (late 1970s): Market reforms privatized agriculture, dramatically increased output, introduced market elements into communist system
  - Chinese citizens "freer and more prosperous than under Mao—freer in every dimension except the political"
  - Small signs of political freedom: village elections for some officials
- **Development doctrine shift**: From "central planning plus massive foreign aid" to market-oriented approach
  - **Peter Bauer** and others demonstrated failure of aid-based development
  - **East Asia tigers** (Hong Kong, Singapore, Taiwan, South Korea) proved market-oriented path
  - Latin America, Asia, even some African countries adopted market approaches
  - Former Soviet satellites followed suit
- **Correlation confirmed**: "Increases in economic freedom have gone hand in hand with increases in political and civil freedom and have led to increased prosperity; competitive capitalism and freedom have been inseparable"

### Reflection on the Book's Endurance
- Rare privilege to evaluate own work 40 years later
- "Enormously gratified by how well the book has withstood time and how pertinent it remains"
- **One major change proposed**: Replace economic/political freedom dichotomy with trichotomy of **economic freedom, civil freedom, and political freedom**
  - **Hong Kong lesson** (before China return): Economic freedom necessary for civil/political freedom, but political freedom not necessary for economic/civil freedom
  - "Under some circumstances promotes economic and civic freedom, and under others, inhibits economic and civic freedom"
- **Major defect identified**: Inadequate treatment of political freedom's role

## Preface, 1982

### Intellectual Climate Shift
- Lectures delivered June 1956 at **Wabash College** (**Volker Foundation** conference)
- 1962 publication: Views "so far out of the mainstream" that major publications (*New York Times*, *Herald Tribune*, *Chicago Tribune*, *Time*, *Newsweek*, *Saturday Review*) ignored it
  - Reviewed by *Economist* and professional journals
  - "Regarded as eccentrics by the great majority of our fellow intellectuals"
- Contrast with 1980: *Free to Choose* reviewed by every major publication, featured in *Book Digest*, mass-market paperback, 400,000 hardcover copies sold in US, translated into 12 languages

### What Changed? Experience, Not Theory
- **Russia and China**: "Once the great hopes of the intellectual classes, had clearly gone sour"
- **Britain's Fabian socialism**: Lost influence over American intellectuals
- **Vietnam War**: Disillusioned intellectuals (Kennedy/Johnson supporters)
- **Great reform programs**: Welfare, public housing, trade union support, school integration, federal education aid, affirmative action "were turning to ashes"
- **Inflation and high taxes** hit pocketbooks
- **Barry Goldwater** overwhelmingly defeated (1964) vs **Ronald Reagan** overwhelmingly victorious (1980)—"two men with essentially the same program and the same message"

### The Role of Ideas in Crisis
- Books provide "subject matter for bull sessions" and help persuade individuals through extended reflection
- More importantly: "Keep options open until circumstances make change necessary"
  - "Enormous inertia—a tyranny of the status quo—in private and especially governmental arrangements"
  - **Crisis produces real change**: "Actions that are taken depend on the ideas that are lying around"
- **Core function**: "Develop alternatives to existing policies, to keep them alive and available until the politically impossible becomes politically inevitable"

### Personal Anecdote: The Draft Debate
- Late 1960s debate at University of Wisconsin with **Leon Keyserling** (unreconstructed collectivist)
- Keyserling read Chapter 2's list of unjustified government activities, mocking Friedman as reactionary
- Point 11 (conscription to man military services) "brought ardent applause and lost him the audience"
- **Draft elimination**: Only item from list of 14 unjustified activities eliminated so far (victory not final)
- Many other items: "We have moved still farther away from the principles espoused in this book"
- Evidence the climate change had little practical effect yet, but also that "fundamental thrust of this book is as pertinent to 1981 as to 1962"

